00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:11.500
that day says, you know what?

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:16.620
I've never tried this before,
but today I'm going to go for it.

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:18.390
Or a surgeon on an
operating table --

00:12:18.390 --> 00:12:22.190
you know, I've done this procedure
for 30 years with my right hand,

00:12:22.190 --> 00:12:25.210
let's see what it feels
like with my left.

00:12:25.210 --> 00:12:27.480
But as a writer, every
day is different.

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:28.820
There is no formula.

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:31.040
There is no template for
what you're supposed to do.

00:12:31.040 --> 00:12:33.980
You just sit down and
try to think of something

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:36.790
that might be interesting to you.

00:12:36.790 --> 00:12:42.630
But if you find a passion in
life, particularly with your work,

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:47.120
treat it as the special moment that
it is because, all of a sudden,

00:12:47.120 --> 00:12:50.520
you have this eureka moment of,
this is how I can spend my life.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:53.400 position:56%
Passion rarely comes around in life,

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:55.370
particularly with what
you do for a living.

00:12:55.370 --> 00:13:00.630
So don't let it pass by -- seize
it, you know, and use it and move

00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:04.050
on with your life and
do that sort of thing.

00:13:04.050 --> 00:13:06.790
You don't want to look back 50 or
60 years from now and wondering,

00:13:06.790 --> 00:13:10.730
you know, maybe I should've decided
and gone down that other path.

00:13:10.730 --> 00:13:13.940
It's worthwhile, I think,
to think about these things.

00:13:13.940 --> 00:13:15.490
My first novel was Absolute Power.

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:18.040
It was about the president,
a burglar, a cover-up,

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:22.940
the truth coming out
and people said, well,

00:13:22.940 --> 00:13:24.710
you were an overnight success.

00:13:24.710 --> 00:13:30.640
And I said, yes, I was, it only
took me 6000 nights to get there.

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:32.170
I just wanted to tell a good story.

00:13:32.170 --> 00:13:34.530
I had no idea that this book
was going to be successful.

00:13:34.530 --> 00:13:38.580
I'd had very little success with my
short stories and my screenplays,

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:42.180
but I've always thought that
if you write with passion,

00:13:42.180 --> 00:13:45.890
that passion will kiss the
words that you're writing about

00:13:45.890 --> 00:13:48.710
and will lift it up out of the
sludge piles that are sitting

00:13:48.710 --> 00:13:50.290
on editors' desks in New York City.

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:52.780
You don't want to write
a trend book.

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:57.290
A trend book is like what's hot,
what's really hot out there.

00:13:57.290 --> 00:14:01.190
I can guarantee you, you know,
when Jurassic Park first came out,

00:14:01.190 --> 00:14:06.100
every script in every book
pitched to anybody had dinosaurs.

00:14:06.100 --> 00:14:09.000
I don't care if it was a romantic
comedy, there was gonna be a,

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.700
you know, a Tyrannosaurus
rex right in the middle

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:15.010
of this little tryst going on.

00:14:15.010 --> 00:14:17.390
Or when the Da Vinci Code
came out, everybody wanted

00:14:17.390 --> 00:14:20.770 position:56%
to write the code book because that
was hot, or the Harry Potter Series,

00:14:20.770 --> 00:14:23.160
everybody wanted to do wizards
and witches and stuff like that.

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:26.430
But if you're not interested in
actually that subject matter,

00:14:26.430 --> 00:14:27.730
guess what's going to happen?

00:14:27.730 --> 00:14:29.260
You're going to run out of gas.

00:14:29.260 --> 00:14:31.260
It could be a quarter of the way
through, half the way through,

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:32.560
and the book's not
going to be that good

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:34.290
because you weren't really
interested in writing it anyway.

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:37.150
You just thought it might sell and
you could sell the movie rights

00:14:37.150 --> 00:14:39.650
and then you could, you
know, fax in your resignation

00:14:39.650 --> 00:14:41.580
from the job you didn't like --

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:45.490
not a really great
motivation to write a book.

00:14:45.490 --> 00:14:47.290
The old adage is, "write
what you know."

00:14:47.290 --> 00:14:49.970
I would modify that
a little bit to say,

00:14:49.970 --> 00:14:53.170
"write what you would
like to know about."

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:55.750
Then you sort of immerse
yourself in a world

00:14:55.750 --> 00:14:58.460
that you really didn't know
before but have been fascinated

00:14:58.460 --> 00:15:00.860
by for a long time and
guess what happens?

00:15:00.860 --> 00:15:02.240
You spend a lot of
time thinking about it.

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:04.420
You spend a lot of time working
on it and, all of a sudden,

00:15:04.420 --> 00:15:07.260
the sentences become better,
the paragraphs become better,

00:15:07.260 --> 00:15:08.940
the chapters become
more enthralling,

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:11.240
the story becomes more powerful.

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:13.300
It really does work that way.

00:15:13.300 --> 00:15:17.650
It's almost like you're putting
the right fuel inside your car.

00:15:17.650 --> 00:15:20.350
Otherwise, if it's just
tracing a trend, you're putting

00:15:20.350 --> 00:15:22.670
in stuff that's just not
going to ignite into anything.

00:15:22.670 --> 00:15:28.060
Now with the Vega Jane
series, I love fantasy.

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:30.090
How many people love
reading fantasy?

00:15:30.090 --> 00:15:32.260
Yeah, it's awesome stuff.

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:35.540
There's a lot of fantasy
going on in DC right now.

00:15:35.540 --> 00:15:37.730
[laughter].

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:40.130
But I will not speak of that.

00:15:40.130 --> 00:15:44.480
But I hear people say it
a lot, so it must be true.

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:50.040
So about, I guess, seven
or eight years ago, my --

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:51.480
like my mother did years before,

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:54.890
my wife gave me a blank
page book for Christmas.

00:15:54.890 --> 00:15:59.240
Do not ever give a writer a
blank paper on a major holiday

00:15:59.240 --> 00:16:01.040
because I immediately ran away

00:16:01.040 --> 00:16:02.530
to my little cubbyhole
and started writing.

00:16:02.530 --> 00:16:05.320
And I wrote this name down on
the first page -- Vega Jane.

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:07.520
I have no idea where
the name came from,

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:09.190
it just sounded really
great and it was in my mind.

00:16:09.190 --> 00:16:13.570
And I wanted to write a
fantasy about Vega Jane and,

00:16:13.570 --> 00:16:16.920
five years later, it was done.

00:16:16.920 --> 00:16:19.760
And it took me about
four-and-a-quarter years

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:23.210
to understand what I wanted to
write about with this person,

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:25.730
what the story was
going to even be about.

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:28.070
But after four-and-a-quarter
years of really thinking about it,

00:16:28.070 --> 00:16:31.350
obsessing about it, then I
wrote the entire first book

00:16:31.350 --> 00:16:34.490
in about seven or eight months.

00:16:34.490 --> 00:16:38.590
And nobody knew I was writing it --
none of my friends, my publisher,

00:16:38.590 --> 00:16:40.820
my agent -- no one,
other than my wife.

00:16:40.820 --> 00:16:43.190
She read it and really enjoyed
it and she is a tough critic.

00:16:43.190 --> 00:16:45.090
I know she's here somewhere.

00:16:45.090 --> 00:16:49.470
You know, I won't ask her to stand
up but I can sense your presence.

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:54.650
And when we sent the
book out to publishers,

00:16:54.650 --> 00:16:56.120
I was adamant about this point.

00:16:56.120 --> 00:17:00.060
I sent the book out under
a pseudonym, a fake name,

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:04.030
because I wanted the book to
be accepted on its merits not

00:17:04.030 --> 00:17:05.340
because my name was attached to it.

00:17:05.340 --> 00:17:09.320
So I used the name Janus Pope --
Janus is the Roman two-faced god.

00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:12.050
I was being very deceitful.

00:17:12.050 --> 00:17:15.550
And Pope was just that
Catholic thing, you know?

00:17:15.550 --> 00:17:17.650
You never know where names
are going to come from.

00:17:17.650 --> 00:17:20.880
So when Scholastic ended up buying
the first book in the series,

00:17:20.880 --> 00:17:23.420
The Finisher, the way
the book is written --

00:17:23.420 --> 00:17:25.660
the terms, colloquialisms
and all that --

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:27.960
they thought I was from England.

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:31.590
So when I went to Scholastic in
New York and introduced myself

00:17:31.590 --> 00:17:35.590
as the author of The Finisher,
they were quite shocked, you know?

00:17:35.590 --> 00:17:38.720
Clifford, you know, the Big
Red Dog, he like fainted.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:41.170
[laughter].

00:17:41.170 --> 00:17:44.690
He's in lobby up there.

00:17:44.690 --> 00:17:45.990
It's like [thud].

00:17:45.990 --> 00:17:49.780
For me, writing that book
was an enormous challenge.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:53.940
I'd never written that genre
before but it's great in life,

00:17:53.940 --> 00:17:56.260
no matter what you do, to
get out of your comfort zone,

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:58.080
you know, to scare yourself.

00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:00.900
People say, you know, what
really drives you as a writer?

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:02.380
And I say fear.

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:05.340
Fear drives me as a
writer, you know?

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:07.990
Can I tell another
good story or not?

00:18:07.990 --> 00:18:10.550
You know, you have this recurring
nightmare that people are going

00:18:10.550 --> 00:18:12.240
to wake up one day
and realize, you know,

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:14.970
you have no idea what
you're doing, you know?

00:18:14.970 --> 00:18:16.920
You ever have that recurring
dream when you're in school

00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:22.600
and you're back in school and
you showed up naked for a test?

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:24.820
Or you haven't been to class
all year and now you have

00:18:24.820 --> 00:18:26.210
to take the exam and
you know nothing

00:18:26.210 --> 00:18:28.330
of what's on there, you know?

00:18:28.330 --> 00:18:30.910
Psychologically, you know,
there's a lot of stuff that goes

00:18:30.910 --> 00:18:34.330
into the interpretive dreams and
they show anxiety in your life,

00:18:34.330 --> 00:18:38.580
loss in your life, some type of
nervous situation you're addressing

00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:41.610
so you dream about it in that
symbolic way and that's why you --

00:18:41.610 --> 00:18:46.340
we all share those dreams because
we share those types of anxieties.

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:48.690
But for me to get out
of my comfort zone

00:18:48.690 --> 00:18:50.250
and write this book was
really important as a writer.

00:18:50.250 --> 00:18:53.000
I think it made me a
better thriller writer

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.230
for having written
this fantasy series.

00:18:56.230 --> 00:18:58.690
So the book came out,
hit number one and,

00:18:58.690 --> 00:19:01.030
you know, was very well-received.

00:19:01.030 --> 00:19:02.560
I used my name when
the book came out --

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:07.170
Scholastic insisted upon that -- I
think it probably did help sales.

00:19:07.170 --> 00:19:10.060 position:56%
But Vega Jane is the lead character.

00:19:10.060 --> 00:19:13.530
She's a young girl and, as
I just mentioned before,

00:19:13.530 --> 00:19:15.530
